## function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Confusion Matrx based findings:¶

  1. Total Positive - Predicted home loan would be accepted and the customer accepted the Personal loan - 77
  2. Total Negative - Precited home loan would not be acceted and the customer didnt accept the loan - 1342
  3. False Positive - Predicted that these customers would accept the loan but these customers declined the loan - 20
  4. False Negative - Predited these customers would not accept loan but these customers accepted or needed personal loan - 61

Metrics:¶

1.Accuracy - Based on the determined Logistics Regression model the Training Accuracy is 93.46% and Testing Accuracy is 94.6% 2.Recall is 55.80% 3.Precision is 79.38% 4.F1 Score: 0.65 5.Roc Auc Score: As per the ROC diagram above the area under the curve is 0.77

Using Logistic Regression model predicting whether customer will take personal loan or not?¶

Looking at the accuracy, 94% accuracy is not small, but we know from the data that the number of loan acceptors percentage to the loan decliners percentage is very less. Hence model accuracy wouldntt play a big role in determining how our model performed

Hence we will look at other measures. Since the objective of the model is to correctly predict the customers who will accept the prsonal loan we need to look at TP and FN as the factors to measure the performance of the model. We must concentrate on reducing type II error i.e. FN, here since we are interested in the customers who had actually bought personal loans, but our model predicted them to be a non-buyer.Therefore, based on the model we need to focus in identifying who are most likely to accept the personal loan, if offered i.e. 77 (TP) + 61 (FN) of the the total i.e. TP + TN + FP + FN. Given the limitations of the mode the offer will instead be made to 77 (TP) + 20 (FP) part of 1500 test data. TP will take personal loan while FP will reject the offer of personal loan. Out of the total number of customers who actually bought personal loans our model is able to pick and correctly predict the TP/(TP+FN) = 77 / 138 = 55.80% of these customers to be correctly predicted.

6. Give Business Understanding of your model.¶

The regression model as described above is to predict whether a customer would accept the bank's personal loan or not. In last year's campaign the acceptability being a mere 10% makes it all the more important for the bank to focus on specific customers to ensure that the conversion rate i.e. the ratio of customers accepting to buy personal loan versus the customers approached by bank to sell its personal loan services. This focussed approach will esnure higher effciciency in usage of bank's resources - both money as we ll as its personnel's time.
